Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in unsupervised relation classification lies in the absence of labeled data to guide both relation discovery and confidence estimation. Most existing methods either rely on heuristics or post-hoc calibration, which fail to produce reliable confidence scores per prediction—especially for individual sentences. Inspired by Papers 1 and 2, I recognize that inconsistency among multiple model outputs (e.g., reasoning paths or generated relations) can serve as a powerful signal of uncertainty. However, unlike these works that focus on LLMs in supervised or prompting settings, my idea shifts the paradigm to fully unsupervised relation extraction, where no ground truth labels exist during training. Paper 3 introduces efficient gradient-based attention overlap as a confidence proxy, but it’s limited to image domains. My insight is to unify semantic self-consistency with multi-view agreement in text, using the *inconsistency* across diverse views (e.g., syntactic, semantic, contextual) not as noise, but as a structured signal to train a confidence-aware classifier. This approach uniquely integrates self-reflection via inconsistency analysis into an end-to-end unsupervised framework, enabling both relation clustering and per-instance confidence learning without any labels. It differs from prior work by jointly modeling confidence and classification through disagreement across views, rather than treating confidence as a post-processing step.

