  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, 'Learning Confidence-Aware Unsupervised Relation Classification via Semantic Self-Consistency and Multi-View Agreement', that enables a relation classifier to assign calibrated confidence scores to predicted relations in individual sentences—without any labeled supervision. The key innovation lies in leveraging inconsistency across multiple semantic and structural views of the same sentence as a supervisory signal for both relation clustering and confidence estimation. Our method generates multiple relation hypotheses for each sentence using diverse input perturbations (e.g., syntactic reordering, paraphrasing, entity masking) and encoder variations (e.g., different attention heads, subnetworks). These hypotheses form a 'multi-view consensus set'. We then compute a semantic self-consistency score based on the alignment of these predictions in a shared relational embedding space, penalizing overconfident outputs when views disagree. Crucially, we introduce a dual-branch architecture: one branch performs unsupervised relation clustering using contrastive learning over sentence pairs, while the second branch learns to predict confidence by modeling the variance, entropy, and semantic coherence across views. The confidence branch is trained using a self-supervised objective that rewards high confidence only when multi-view agreement is high and semantically consistent—mimicking the 'mirror' reflection mechanism in Mirror-Consistency, but applied to structural linguistic inputs rather than reasoning chains. To enhance semantic sensitivity, we incorporate a lightweight gradient-based attention overlap module (inspired by Over-MAP) that measures alignment between salient tokens in dependency paths and contextual embeddings, providing an efficient, non-sampling-based confidence cue. This integrated signal is used to modulate the final confidence output. The entire system is trained end-to-end using a joint loss combining cluster consistency, semantic agreement, and confidence calibration (via implicit negative feedback from low-agreement instances). By doing so, our model not only discovers coherent relation types from raw text but also learns to express epistemic uncertainty at the instance level. This has significant implications for downstream applications like knowledge base construction, where high-confidence predictions can be prioritized for human review or direct integration. Unlike SaySelf, which requires synthetic supervision and fine-tuning, our method operates entirely without labels. Compared to traditional bootstrapping or clustering baselines, it explicitly models and leverages disagreement as a feature, turning a common weakness into a strength. The result is a more trustworthy, transparent, and robust unsupervised relation classifier.",
  "Title": "Confidence-Aware Unsupervised Relation Classification via Semantic Self-Consistency and Multi-View Agreement",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of four phases. Phase 1: Data preprocessing on standard benchmarks (e.g., NYT, Wikipedia, or OpenWebText) to extract subject-object pairs and context sentences. We apply syntactic parsing and entity linking to generate multiple views per sentence. Phase 2: Model architecture implementation using a dual-encoder transformer with multi-view augmentation (paraphrases, syntax trees, masked variants). The relation clustering branch uses contrastive learning with hard negative mining; the confidence branch takes as input the distribution of predicted clusters across views, attention overlap maps, and semantic similarity scores (using BERTScore among views). Phase 3: Training with a joint loss: (a) InfoNCE loss for clustering, (b) KL-divergence minimization across views for self-consistency, and (c) variance-penalized confidence regression where low-agreement instances are assigned lower confidence targets. No manual labels are used. Phase 4: Evaluation using pseudo-labels derived from distant supervision (for clustering accuracy: NMI, ARI) and held-out expert-annotated subsets (for confidence calibration: ECE, AUROC for detecting low-confidence/incorrect predictions). Baselines include K-means on BERT embeddings, CODER, and Self-Consistency clustering. We also ablate components (e.g., remove multi-view, remove attention overlap) to assess contribution. Ideal outcomes: (1) Clustering performance matches or exceeds current unsupervised methods; (2) High-confidence predictions show >90% precision even in low-density clusters; (3) Confidence scores strongly correlate with prediction correctness (AUROC > 0.85); (4) Attention overlap correlates with human-judged ambiguity.",
